subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis. This new species resembles
S. tumefacta
sp. nov.
( Figs 53 A–E, 54A–D, 55A–B) in having a thin embolus with a reduced embolic apophysis and lateral lobes fused, with almost horizontal margins anteriorly, but can be separated by: 1. Male palp with dRTA narrow and dorsally digitiform (wide, bulging in
S. tumefacta
); 2. Female vulva with glandular appendages short (long in
S. tumefacta
), posterior parts of spermathecae distinctly swollen (slightly swollen in
S. tumefacta
).
